topic.title: How to manage identities?
topic.body: When I open the site menu, I can choose different identities to use, but I don't know how to remove any of them. Is there some identity manager that I can use to remove my identities or is it just a matter of deleting a single file somewhere?

> [unadu](#comment_23_16tiWQCvXDH6r8GWNGUzvvnAHqN89eX72W): There is the multiuser plugin that you can enable in Hello-Page -> Three dots -> Plugins. This plugin then manages the IDs with cookies and allows you to remove one and reuse another one or just creating a new one. [...]

This is really useful information, thanks! I have managed to remove the unneeded identities just by editing the users.json file you mentioned.

> [trevorlaneray](#comment_50_12eXcQ1ojAbyCoCcMQ3JAKi73wgcJrjow3): Hmm...Is there a way to correctly edit the users.json file to manually delete/add your identities?I mean, if so, I'd like to understand how, then write an AutoHotKey script GUI to parse users.json and allow management of identities.This way, I could avoid resorting to cookies (blegh) for identity management.If I were to enable the multiuser plugin, I'm assuming this would effectively replace the functionality of the users.json file. Once I do, wouldn't this mean I'd have a difficult time porting those cookies back into the users.json file?Cookies aren't exactly the way I'd like to manage identities, since they're easily (irrevocably) deleted during common cleaning tasks (i.e.: CCleaner & etc).

Yeah it's easy to just manage them through the json file. You can edit any field, delete them and easily back them up. That's all I needed!

> [trevorlaneray](#comment_51_12eXcQ1ojAbyCoCcMQ3JAKi73wgcJrjow3): Wait, if the multiuser plugin uses cookies to manage identities, does it export identities from users.json to cookies, but not use the users.json file once you start using it?Or does it keep users.json file up-to-date with the cookie-based identities you create and manage?

I'd love to tell you, but I have no idea. I just started experimenting with ZeroNet a few days ago and I'm still figuring things out, hence this thread.

> [trevorlaneray](#comment_53_12eXcQ1ojAbyCoCcMQ3JAKi73wgcJrjow3): ... I'm so confused right now. ^u^

That's why I don't always experiment with everything. If what I want can be achieved by deleting a few lines in a file, I'd rather avoid turning on experimental plugins and running into problems like @unadu did. This whole system appears to be a bit iffy so I'd rather take it slow and feel the waters before playing around with any advanced features. Also, what does the "u" in ^u^ mean? Is it the mouth or the nose?

> [bigbadbob](#comment_748_1CLhLYdMKjXtium9yjuRkSnFvPfdoUTXAj): It will pass if you let it op :) We tend to gloss over anything good that may be happening and its natural to focus on the bad shit we face.  I try to stay excited with the future because everything is unknown.  Things may seem like a train wreck but how will it all play out?  The wonder keeps me going. We are alive so we are doing ok and there is always a chance something amazing could happen. Excitement and fresh new experiences are always outside of our comfort zone.

Hey, I'd like to chime in and ask - what if someone doesn't care about the future? I feel like I'm in that boat since I am aware of how big the universe is and how oh so special/complex life is, but I just can't bring myself to care about that really. I don't even know how to put it into words, it's hard to describe how little I care about that.

It's the environment I was born in and my choice is to either live in it or kill myself. It's not like "oh wow this universe is so cool compared to that old shitty one". As far as I know, this is the only one I can inhabit and that's why I really don't care about how complex or simple it is. If I may say, it is what it is. Care to explain how you get yourself to be so high on life to an anon who hates it?

> [bigbadbob](#comment_757_1CLhLYdMKjXtium9yjuRkSnFvPfdoUTXAj): Typically if you do not care about your future you probably lack goals. If your environment sucks an obvious goal would be to better it. How do you know the universe is soo big? Is it because that's what people say? What do you know as fact based on your own experience disregarding all you have been told? The universe can be as big or as small as you like it to be, if its so big that you feel meaningless then you might want to zoom the scope in so you can see yourself and your surroundings and focus on that.  To a certain degree happiness is a choice and could be a goal.  Figure out what you would want and go for it.  Waiting for something brings nothing.  The comfort zone is like as tar pit.  It goes nowhere.  Do you have goals or dreams?

Well yeah, I do lack goals. I thought I had some sound goals, but once I started achieving them I realized they definitely do not justify this existence. I'm trying to figure out why should I keep getting out of my bed every morning. I do because I need to hold a job so I can pay for food and rent, but why do all that stuff? That's the question which has been stuck in my head for some time now.

> If your environment sucks an obvious goal would be to better it. How do you know the universe is soo big? Is it because that's what people say? What do you know as fact based on your own experience disregarding all you have been told? The universe can be as big or as small as you like it to be, if its so big that you feel meaningless then you might want to zoom the scope in so you can see yourself and your surroundings and focus on that.

I'm just citing what people say, I don't really care either way. This universe can be as big or small as it wants, I doubt I could care less. You're right about the scoping in bit which is probably how most people give themselves purpose, but I don't think it's a proper solution or an answer, it's just blocking everything that's not immediately around you. What about "the bigger picture"?

> To a certain degree happiness is a choice and could be a goal. Figure out what you would want and go for it. Waiting for something brings nothing. The comfort zone is like as tar pit. It goes nowhere. Do you have goals or dreams?

You're unfortunately right, I have a very small comfort zone that I cherish more than everything. I despise new experiences and I just stick to what works. It's such a bother even trying out new video games. Why would I do that if I can just play this same one and have fun with it. Getting new experiences is such a bother, man.

Regarding happiness, I don't think it's a choice but it definitely is a goal, or at least should be. And about the goals, I did have some very stupid and superficial goals but as I've said, I have recently found them completely inadequate as they do not justify dealing with various stuff in life. It all seems so stupid, man. The human condition kinda deal, you get born, you experience shit and you die. All that for what? Why not just skip all the experience and jump straight into death? You don't get to experience positive things but at least you don't get to experience the negative things either.

Sorry if I rambled but you touched on so many things that I'd like to talk about so it's a mess.

> [bigbadbob](#comment_769_1CLhLYdMKjXtium9yjuRkSnFvPfdoUTXAj): It gets old but there is a way to break free and for now its called real estate,  Buying a house is better then renting and if you had a few you wouldn't need to work. just collect rent and do fixes once in a while. It's a challange to get to this point as i am not there myself. but it's something i find interesting.  If i had like three or four rental units i wouldn't need to work, but if i did work that be better.  It's a goal cause i hate the grind.

Rent was just an example, even if I had my own place where I didn't need to pay rent, I still need to pay for other necessities. My point was, why put in any work into anything? It's possible that this is a very stupid question, but when you go with the mindset of "nothing matters and we'll all die", that question starts sounding a lot more reasonable hopefully.

> [bigbadbob](#comment_769_1CLhLYdMKjXtium9yjuRkSnFvPfdoUTXAj): There is nothing wrong with observing the big picture so long as you do not loose focus on yourself. I struggle with this all the time.

Yeah but when you start observing the big picture, you inevitably start seeing yourself as smaller and smaller in comparison. Yeah I can paint the walls of my room or help my friend fix his car, but it's all completely pointless once you zoom out. Why bother with all of that stuff?

> [bigbadbob](#comment_769_1CLhLYdMKjXtium9yjuRkSnFvPfdoUTXAj): The comfort zone is comfy but it's depressing. Time goes by and still doing the same thing. It's adventurous to take risks and wing it. Everytime i go out of my comfort zone and take a risk i'm am usually glad i did, You only live once and if you are not afraid of death... what the worst that can happen?

Yeah I kinda have to agree about this. I do get a thrill out of succeeding at something new and risky that's out of my comfort zone, but I also get extremely frustrated and sad when I fail. Interestingly enough, for some reason the thrill lasts a lot less compared to the emptiness and frustration which really makes me think all this work and stress is for nothing. What's the worst that can happen you ask? A lot of things come to mind, actually.

I could end up wasting my whole life searching for some meaning but eventually I just become old, alone and even more confused. Maybe I'll subconsciously lie myself into having some really stupid goal so I end up living my life like a suburban dad, where everything is kinda okay but deep down inside he's just counting the minutes until the time where he can finally be free from this prison he ended up in.

What if there's life after death, and that life is in hell? That means you waste all of your life here just to end up being tortured for eternity. What if there's no afterlife at all? That makes this life absolutely pointless. Why exist for 7-8 dozen years and then just stop existing completely? It all seems stupid and pointless and it's fucking driving me nuts. The more I talk to people about this the less clear everything fucking becomes. Everyone has some superficial faggy goals like "oh I want as much enjoyment as possible" or "I want to help as many people as possible" or "I want to save the planet from x, y, z"... Fucking why?!

I wish I could just return to not existing for an eternity. Not feeling or experiencing or thinking about anything for an eternity, because anything else is just a waste of time and energy.

> [goodafternoon](#comment_19_1BL1pFELvZ58apCLcxogy2W66aC4vKLfY3): Why do you seek destruction? What do you get out of it if you've never seen this person before?

He's not seeking destruction, he's just answering the question. Also, in your previous reply you were wondering why would anyone want to jump to their life's end. Maybe I didn't read your reply correctly, but I think a pretty obvious answer is hardships in life. People have various problems that they don't know how to overcome, and they feel like giving up is a better or easier option. They choose the option to feel nothing instead of feeling both sadness and joy (in differing ratios, of course). > [bigbadbob](#comment_830_1CLhLYdMKjXtium9yjuRkSnFvPfdoUTXAj): Why not suicide by natural causes?  Just wait... It will happen eventually.

Because suicide by natural causes usually hurts and is very slow. The helium option mentioned below seems a lot more effective than what you suggest.

> [bigbadbob](#comment_832_1CLhLYdMKjXtium9yjuRkSnFvPfdoUTXAj): Pain is a state of mind,   no one ever got anywhere staying inside the comfort zone.  Rather than die... why not learn to have fun doing crazy shit?  Death could be a by-product,  or reward could be another.

Pain probably is just a state of mind, but my entire consciousness lies in that mind! I can't just be in pain and think "ah yes I am in a painful state of mind now, how inconvenient..." because that's all that I am feeling! I can't rise above it. I don't even wanna consider "doing crazy shit" given how much pain that can bring me. Suicide is a way to end the pain, not to keep living through varying amounts of it.
Also, comfort zone is called a comfort zone for a reason - it's comfortable... And I reeeeally love being comfortable!
